<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1323,1463,1889]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">
Material examined. 
<collectingCountry box="[510,688,1463,1489]" name="South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">South Georgia</collectingCountry>
, Grytviken: 
<specimenCount box="[844,1006,1463,1489]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" type="generic">
<number box="[844,872,1463,1489]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="11.0">11</number>
specimens
</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[1074,1155,1463,1489]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" type="egg">
<number box="[1074,1089,1463,1489]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="4.0">4</number>
eggs
</specimenCount>
from a moss sample.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1323,1463,1889]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">Unfortunately the quality of some photos is not optimal due to the quality of the specimens.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1323,1463,1889]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">
Specimens and eggs found by Dastych in 
<collectingCountry box="[820,992,1623,1649]" name="South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">South Georgia</collectingCountry>
perfectly coincide with the description of 
<emphasis box="[443,585,1663,1688]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">
<taxonomicName box="[443,581,1663,1688]" class="Eutardigrada" family="Macrobiotidae" genus="Macrobiotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Parachela" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="species" species="furciger">M. furciger</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
We think it opportune to add some notes to make a more detailed description of the species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1323,1463,1889]" lastBlockId="2.[264,1322,284,430]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="57" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">
Description. Cuticle smooth, colourless, eyes present; buccopharyngeal apparatus of 
<taxonomicName box="[264,413,1783,1808]" class="Eutardigrada" family="Macrobiotidae" genus="Macrobiotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Parachela" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[264,413,1783,1808]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">Macrobiotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus box="[422,472,1783,1809]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">type</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation box="[490,561,1783,1809]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[264,367,1560,1584]" captionTargetBox="[267,1319,473,1548]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[267,1320,468,1558]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Macrobiotus furciger Murray, 1906: A, buccopharyngeal apparatus; B, buccopharyngeal apparatus where the shape of the stylet sheaths is focused; C, claws of the hind legs; D, E, details of the egg. (Scale bar = 10 m)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273290/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">
Fig. 
<number box="[546,561,1783,1809]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
A, B); mouth terminal with ten peribuccal lamellae, an anterior band of small teeth, a posterior ring of triangular teeth, three dorsal and three ventral transverse ridges. Also some supplementary teeth may be present. Stylet supports inserted on the buccal tube at 
<number box="[550,668,284,310]" pageId="2" pageNumber="57" value="76.65" valueMax="77.1" valueMin="76.2">76.2–77.1</number>
% of its length (
<emphasis box="[884,907,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="57">pt</emphasis>
= 
<number box="[952,1073,284,310]" pageId="2" pageNumber="57" value="76.65" valueMax="77.1" valueMin="76.2">76.2–77.1</number>
). Other notes about dimensional characters are indicated in 
<tableCitation box="[745,837,324,350]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="3.[264,352,643,667]" captionTargetBox="[264,1294,814,1896]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 1. Dimensions of some structures of the smallest and the largest measured specimens of Macrobiotus furciger, M. aradasi sp. nov., M. divergens sp. nov. and M. sicheli sp. nov." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/BA8066059661FF98FEEFA9881890FD62" pageId="2" pageNumber="57" tableUuid="BA8066059661FF98FEEFA9881890FD62">
Table 
<number box="[821,837,324,350]" pageId="2" pageNumber="57" value="1.0">1</number>
</tableCitation>
. Pharyngeal bulb with apophyses, three rod­shaped macroplacoids without narrowings, microplacoid present. Third macroplacoid clearly longer than the first two (
<tableCitation box="[648,736,404,430]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="3.[264,352,643,667]" captionTargetBox="[264,1294,814,1896]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 1. Dimensions of some structures of the smallest and the largest measured specimens of Macrobiotus furciger, M. aradasi sp. nov., M. divergens sp. nov. and M. sicheli sp. nov." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/BA8066059661FF98FEEFA9881890FD62" pageId="2" pageNumber="57" tableUuid="BA8066059661FF98FEEFA9881890FD62">
Table 
<number box="[722,736,404,430]" pageId="2" pageNumber="57" value="1.0">1</number>
</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273290/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="57" targetBox="[267,1319,473,1548]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,1560,1653]" pageId="2" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,406,1560,1584]" pageId="2" pageNumber="57">FIGURE 1</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Murray, 1906" authorityName="Murray" authorityYear="1906" box="[438,876,1561,1584]" class="Eutardigrada" family="Macrobiotidae" genus="Macrobiotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Parachela" pageId="2" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="species" species="furciger">
<emphasis box="[438,683,1561,1584]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="57">Macrobiotus furciger</emphasis>
Murray, 1906
</taxonomicName>
: A, buccopharyngeal apparatus; B, buccopharyngeal apparatus where the shape of the stylet sheaths is focused; C, claws of the hind legs; D, E, details of the egg. (Scale bar = 10 m)
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,1705,1891]" pageId="2" pageNumber="57">
Claws of the 
<emphasis box="[468,579,1705,1730]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="57">hufelandi</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[587,637,1705,1731]" pageId="2" pageNumber="57">type</typeStatus>
well developed and with very developed accessory points on main branches (
<figureCitation box="[486,555,1745,1771]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[264,367,1560,1584]" captionTargetBox="[267,1319,473,1548]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[267,1320,468,1558]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Macrobiotus furciger Murray, 1906: A, buccopharyngeal apparatus; B, buccopharyngeal apparatus where the shape of the stylet sheaths is focused; C, claws of the hind legs; D, E, details of the egg. (Scale bar = 10 m)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273290/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="57">
Fig. 
<number box="[540,555,1745,1771]" pageId="2" pageNumber="57" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
C). Lunules present, smooth on the first three pairs of legs, finely indented on the hind legs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,1705,1891]" lastBlockId="3.[264,1324,284,590]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="58" pageId="2" pageNumber="57">
Eggs laid freely, spherical, diameter 
<quantity box="[743,921,1825,1851]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.605" metricValueMax="10.04" metricValueMin="9.17" pageId="2" pageNumber="57" unit="m" value="96.05" valueMax="100.4" valueMin="91.7">91.7–100.4 m</quantity>
excluding the processes, 
<quantity metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.165" metricValueMax="1.23" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="2" pageNumber="57" unit="m" value="116.5" valueMax="123.0" valueMin="110.0">110–123 m</quantity>
processes included. Distal portion of the processes (
<quantity box="[920,1024,1865,1891]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.588" metricValueMax="6.096" metricValueMin="5.08" pageId="2" pageNumber="57" unit="in" value="22.0" valueMax="24.0" valueMin="20.0">20–24 in</quantity>
the circumference) twice or thrice divided; the terminal branches appear as short terminal points (
<figureCitation box="[1109,1178,284,310]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[264,367,1560,1584]" captionTargetBox="[267,1319,473,1548]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[267,1320,468,1558]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Macrobiotus furciger Murray, 1906: A, buccopharyngeal apparatus; B, buccopharyngeal apparatus where the shape of the stylet sheaths is focused; C, claws of the hind legs; D, E, details of the egg. (Scale bar = 10 m)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273290/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[1164,1178,284,310]" pageId="3" pageNumber="58" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
D, E). Each subdivision may be dichotomic or multiple, 
<emphasis box="[802,845,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="58">i.e.,</emphasis>
two or more branches may be formed. Process surface has some small refracting areas (
<figureCitation box="[839,909,364,390]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[264,367,1560,1584]" captionTargetBox="[267,1319,473,1548]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[267,1320,468,1558]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Macrobiotus furciger Murray, 1906: A, buccopharyngeal apparatus; B, buccopharyngeal apparatus where the shape of the stylet sheaths is focused; C, claws of the hind legs; D, E, details of the egg. (Scale bar = 10 m)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273290/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[894,909,364,390]" pageId="3" pageNumber="58" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
D, E), some larger refracting areas are in the distal portion and in the branches (this character has been noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Murray" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" refString="Murray, J. (1906) Scottish national Antarctic expedition: Tardigrada of the South Orkneys. Transactions of the Royal Society of Edinburgh, 45, Part 2 (12), 323 - 334." type="journal article" year="1906">
Murray, 
<number box="[264,327,444,470]" pageId="3" pageNumber="58" value="1906.0">1906</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). In the largest measured egg the processes are 
<quantity box="[886,1005,444,470]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="3" pageNumber="58" unit="m" value="12.5" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="12.0">12–13 m</quantity>
high; the basal diameter is variable from 
<quantity box="[430,598,484,510]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.275" metricValueMax="1.45" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="3" pageNumber="58" unit="m" value="12.75" valueMax="14.5" valueMin="11.0">11 to 14.5 m</quantity>
. The base of each process has many short digitations forming a ring of dots; the egg shell has many small refracting points and therefore it has a reticular sculpture with very small meshes.
</paragraph>
