Remarks. 
<collectingCountry box="[436,469,284,310]" name="American Samoa" pageId="4" pageNumber="59">As</collectingCountry>
above mentioned, we compared material from different geographical areas. 
<bibRefCitation author="Dastych" box="[346,534,324,350]" pageId="4" pageNumber="68" refString="Dastych, H. (1984) The Tardigrada from Antarctic with description of several new species. Acta Zoologica Cracoviensia, 27 (19), 377 - 436." type="journal article" year="1984">
Dastych (
<number box="[465,526,324,350]" pageId="4" pageNumber="59" value="1984.0">1984</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
studied specimens (and eggs) from 
<collectingCountry box="[1003,1180,324,350]" name="South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands" pageId="4" pageNumber="59">South Georgia</collectingCountry>
and South 
<collectingCountry box="[264,464,364,390]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="4" pageNumber="59">Shetland Islands</collectingCountry>
, described some differences concerning both animals and eggs but he attributed all specimens and eggs to 
<emphasis box="[691,829,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="59">
<taxonomicName box="[691,825,404,429]" class="Eutardigrada" family="Macrobiotidae" genus="Macrobiotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Parachela" pageId="4" pageNumber="59" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="species" species="furciger">M. furciger</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
In our opinion the specimens from 
<collectingCountry name="South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands" pageId="4" pageNumber="59">South Georgia</collectingCountry>
belong to 
<taxonomicName box="[493,744,444,469]" class="Eutardigrada" family="Macrobiotidae" genus="Macrobiotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Parachela" pageId="4" pageNumber="59" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="species" species="furciger">
